Optimal Route Planning: Cost and Time Optimization with Real-World Data

1. Business Context

Efficient route planning is a critical challenge for many industries, from logistics and e-commerce to retail operations. Optimizing routes can help reduce travel time, fuel consumption, and operational costs, while improving sustainability and customer satisfaction.

This project demonstrates how data-driven optimization techniques can be applied to identify the most efficient route between two locations, using real-world data retrieved from public APIs.

2. Definition of the problem

The goal of this project is to determine where to stop and how much fuel to refill along a given route for a vehicle using a specific type of fuel.

This project consists of two parts, each with a different optimization objective:

  1. Part A Minimize Fuel Cost: The objective is to minimize the total refueling cost while satisfying fuel capacity and safety constraints.
  2. Part B Minimize Travel Time: The objective is to minimize the total travel time along the route, while still respecting the vehicle's fuel constraints and safety margins.

Both parts use the same underlying data and modeling approach, but the assumptions and priorities are adapted depending on the chosen objective.

2.1 Part A - Minimize Fuel Cost

The model takes into account the following known parameters:

  • Maximum tank capacity: the maximum amount of fuel (in liters or kilograms) that the vehicle can hold.
  • Minimum tank level: the minimum amount of fuel that must remain in the tank at all times (including upon arrival). This acts as a safety buffer to ensure the vehicle never runs out of fuel.
  • Initial fuel level: the starting amount of fuel in the tank, which must lie between the minimum and maximum capacity.
  • Fuel consumption: assumed to be constant throughout the trip, measured in L/100 km or kg/100 km depending on the fuel type.

2.1.1 Modeling Assumptions

To simplify the formulation, the following assumptions are made:

  • The vehicle only makes detours to refuel. If refueling is not needed, it follows the original route without deviation.
  • All selected gas stations always have the required fuel available, regardless of the refueling amount.
  • A minimum refueling payment of 5 is required at each stop (e.g., due to card payment constraints).
  • Fuel prices are assumed to be fixed along the route once downloaded from the official APIs.
  • The detour distance to reach a gas station is added both ways (going to and returning from the station).
    For example, if a gas station is located at 528.8 km from the start and requires a 20.5 km detour, the total distance traveled when returning to the main route will be: $528.8 + 2 \times 20.5 = 569.8 \text{ km}$
  • Only gas stations located on the right side of the road (side = D) or on both sides (side = N) are considered accessible, avoiding extra detours for U-turns.
  • It is assumed that the vehicle can always return to the main route after refueling without additional distance overhead.

2.1.2 Objective: Cost Optimization

The first goal of the analysis is to minimize the total cost of refueling over the entire trip.

The optimization model determines:

  • The set of gas stations where stops should be made.
  • The amount of fuel to refill at each selected station.
  • The total travel distance, total cost, and remaining fuel upon arrival.

2.1.3 Experimental Setup

To illustrate the approach, the route between Madrid and Barcelona is used as an example.
Different fuel types are compared based on their consumption and tank capacity:

Fuel Type Tank Capacity Consumption
Gasoline 95/98/Premium 50 L 7 L / 100 km
Diesel A/Premium 60 L 5 L / 100 km
LPG 30 L 9 L / 100 km
CNG 20 kg 4.5 kg / 100 km
LNG 80 kg 3.5 kg / 100 km

For all cases:

  • The safety margin is equivalent to the fuel required for 60 km.
  • The vehicle starts the trip with half a tank.

2.1.4 Problem Formulation

Known parameters:

  • $r_i$: Distance from the start of the route to the exit leading to gas station $i = 1,\dots, N$, with $N$ being the total number of gas stations that offer the selected fuel type along the route (on the right side or on both sides).

  • $r_0 = 0$ and $r_{N+1}$ is the total length (in km) of the route.

  • $C$: Fuel consumption rate in L/100km or kg/100km, depending on the fuel type.

  • $d_i$: Distance of the detour from point $r_i$ on the route to gas station $i$, with $i = 1,\dots, N$.

  • $p_i$: Fuel price at gas station $i$, with $i = 1,\dots, N$.

  • $c_{max}$: Maximum fuel tank capacity.

  • $c_{min}$: Minimum required fuel level in the tank.

Decision variables:

  • $l_{i}$: Amount of fuel refilled (in liters or kilograms) at gas station $i = 1,\dots, N$.

  • $x_i$: Binary variable indicating whether to stop at gas station $i$ or not, $i = 1,\dots, N$.

We also define the following auxiliary variables to simplify the problem formulation:

  • $c_{i}$: Amount of fuel in the tank at point $r_i$, $i = 0,\dots, N+1$.

  • Objective function: minimize the total fuel cost:

$$\min \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^N p_i\, l_i$$

  • Define $c_i$ as the amount of fuel in the tank at each point before the detour:

$$c_i = c_0 + \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{i-1} l_j - \dfrac{C}{100} \left( r_i + 2 \displaystyle\sum_{j=1}^{i-1} d_j x_j \right) \quad \forall i=1,\dots,N+1 $$

  • Minimum fuel constraint:

$$ c_{i}\geq c_{min} + \dfrac{C}{100} d_i x_i \quad \forall i=1,\dots,N$$

$$c_{N+1}\geq c_{min}$$

  • Maximum fuel constraint:

$$c_i + l_i - \dfrac{C}{100} d_i x_i \leq c_{max} \quad \forall i=1,\dots,N$$

  • Minimum refueling (5) constraint if stopping at a gas station:

$$p_i l_i \geq 5 x_i \quad \forall i=1,\dots,N$$

  • Constraint to enforce zero refueling if the binary variable is zero:

$$l_i \leq c_{max} x_i \quad \forall i=1,\dots,N$$

  • Sign and binary constraints:

$$x_i \in \{0,1\},\quad l_i\geq 0, \quad c_i \geq 0 \quad \forall i=1,\dots,N$$

2.2 Part B - Minimize travel time

In this part, the focus shifts from minimizing cost to minimizing time. The priority is to travel the route as quickly as possible (i.e., minimizing detours) rather than using cheaper gas stations. Therefore, the objective is reformulated as minimizing the total time required to complete the route, including refueling stops.

Some additional assumptions are required for this objective:

  • Stops are only for refueling, without considering additional breaks for rest, meals, restroom, etc.

  • The time required to refuel at a gas station is broken down into:

    • A fixed component of 5 minutes, assumed to cover waiting at the pump and payment.
    • A variable component proportional to the amount of fuel, assuming a pump rate of 20 L/min (or kg/min for gaseous fuels).

  • Travel speed (in km/h) is inferred from OpenRouteService and, similar to fuel consumption, is assumed constant. In other words, factors such as traffic jams, accidents, construction, adverse weather, or speed limits in towns are not considered.

  • Additionally, as mentioned in the previous point, we assume that the same average speed can be maintained during the detour to the gas station (both going and returning).

Assuming we refuel with 15 L, the total time includes:

  • The 5 minutes spent at the station for stopping and payment.
  • The 15 / 20 = 0.75 minutes required for the actual refueling.
  • The time needed to travel the 2*20.5 = 41 km detour at 100.56 km/h.

2.2.1 Problem Formulation

If we consider only the gas stations that are open 24 hours, we need to change the objective function to minimize the detour time, since the speed on the road and the route itself are assumed constant.

Thus, using the same variables defined in Part A, we add the following:

We define a new parameter:

  • v: speed along the route (in km/h).
  • Objective function: minimize the time spent at each gas station, taking into account the fixed 5 minutes, the time the pump takes to deliver each liter, and the detour required to reach the station (assuming constant speed).

$$\min \displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^N \left( 2\dfrac{d_i}{v} + \dfrac{5}{60}\right)x_i + \dfrac{l_i}{20\cdot 60} \quad i =1,\dots, N$$

  • No additional constraints are necessary.

3.2 Municipalities, Provinces, and Autonomous Communities of Spain

Additionally, the Ministry provides, through the same API, geographical context, allowing us to obtain the lists and names of municipalities, provinces, and autonomous communities.

In Spain, this hierarchy is strict: a municipality can belong to only one province, and a province in turn belongs to a single autonomous community. Therefore, it is sufficient to know, for each municipality, its name and the province it belongs to in order to uniquely identify it:

In[10]:
def get_municipalities() -> pd.DataFrame:

        .astype({'mun_id': int, 'prov_id': int}).set_index('mun_id').sort_index()
    )

3.3 Fuel Stations

All this geographical information is relevant because service stations (gas stations) across the country are catalogued according to their corresponding municipalities.

Since we also have their exact locations in the form of (longitude, latitude), we store all the information as a GeoDataFrame using geopandas:

In[21]:
def get_stations() -> gpd.GeoDataFrame:
    response = requests.get("https://sedeaplicaciones.minetur.gob.es/ServiciosRESTCarburantes/PreciosCarburantes/EstacionesTerrestres/")
    stations = (
        pd.DataFrame(response.json()['ListaEESSPrecio'])
        [['IDEESS', 'Rtulo', 'Margen', 'Direccin', 'IDMunicipio', 'Horario', 'Latitud', 'Longitud (WGS84)']]
        .rename(columns={
            'IDEESS': 'stat_id', 'Rtulo': 'brand', 'Margen': 'side', 'Direccin': 'address', 'IDMunicipio': 'mun_id', 'Horario': 'open_times',
            'Latitud': 'lat', 'Longitud (WGS84)': 'lon',
        })
        .assign(**{'lat': lambda x: x['lat'].str.replace(',', '.'), 'lon': lambda x: x['lon'].str.replace(',', '.')}).astype({'lat': float, 'lon': float})
        .astype({'stat_id': int, 'mun_id': int}).set_index('stat_id').sort_index()
    )
    return (
        gpd.GeoDataFrame(
            stations.drop(columns=['lat', 'lon']),
            geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(stations['lon'], stations['lat'], crs="WGS84"),
        )
        .rename_geometry('location')
    )

stations = get_stations()

3.4 Fuel Prices

For each of these gas stations, the Ministry updates the fuel prices approximately every 30 minutes.

Not all gas stations sell every type of fuel. While most stations offer at least Diesel A (fuel_id = 4) and Gasoline 95 (fuel_id = 1), there are less common fuels such as LPG or CNG.

The prices DataFrame constructed below contains one entry (price) for each gas station (stat_id) and fuel type (fuel_id) that the station offers:

In[26]:
def get_fuel_prices(fuels: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    response = requests.get("https://sedeaplicaciones.minetur.gob.es/ServiciosRESTCarburantes/PreciosCarburantes/EstacionesTerrestres/")
    prices = pd.DataFrame(response.json()['ListaEESSPrecio'])
    price_cols = [col for col in prices.columns if col.startswith('Precio')]
    prices = prices[['IDEESS'] + price_cols]
    for col in price_cols:
        prices.loc[:, col] = prices[col].str.replace(',', '.').replace('', 'nan')
    prices = (
        prices
        .astype({'IDEESS': int} | {col: float for col in price_cols})
        .rename(columns=({'IDEESS': 'stat_id'}))
        .set_index('stat_id').sort_index()
    )
    prices_stacked = []
    for col in price_cols:
        c = col.removeprefix('Precio ').replace('Gasoleo', 'Gasleo').replace('Hidrogeno', 'Hidrgeno').replace('Biodiesel', 'Biodisel')
        fuel_id = [f_id for f_id, f_c in fuels['fuel_name'].items() if f_c.lower().startswith(c.lower())][0]
        prices_stacked.append((
            prices.loc[~prices[col].isna(), [col]]
            .rename(columns={col: 'price'})
            .assign(**{'fuel_id': fuel_id})
            .set_index('fuel_id', append=True)
        ))
    return pd.concat(prices_stacked, axis=0).sort_index()

prices = get_fuel_prices(fuels)

3.5 Routes

To work with routes, we will use the API from OpenRouteService.

In[29]:
API_KEY = "API_KEY"

The following function determines the recommended route between two points, start and end, given by their (lon, lat) coordinates, by calling the OpenRouteService API:

In[30]:
from shapely.geometry import Point, LineString
from typing import Dict, Any

ORS_URL = "https://api.openrouteservice.org/v2/directions/driving-car"

def get_route(start: Point, end: Point, api_key: str) -> Dict[str, Any]:
    headers = {
        "Authorization": api_key,
        "Content-Type": "application/json",
        "Accept": "application/json, application/geo+json, application/gpx+xml, img/png; charset=utf-8",
    }
    body = {
        "coordinates": [[start.x, start.y], [end.x, end.y]],
        "units": "km",
        "instructions": "false",
        "options": {
            "avoid_features": ["ferries"],
            "avoid_borders": "controlled",
            "avoid_countries": ["FR", "AD", "PT"],
        },
    }
    response = requests.post(ORS_URL, json=body, headers=headers)
    route = response.json()['routes'][0]
    return {
        'geometry': LineString(decode_polyline(route['geometry'], geojson=True)),
        'distance': route['summary']['distance'],
        'duration': route['summary']['duration'],
        'bbox': route['bbox'],
    }

The result is a dictionary with four fields:

  • geometry: the route path, given as a list of linear segments (LineString), one after another.
  • distance: the total length of the route (in km).
  • duration: the estimated total time (in seconds) to traverse the entire route (without stops).
  • bbox: the coordinates defining the bounding box of the route (rectangle specified by the southwest and northeast corners).

A route in this format can be plotted on an interactive folium map using the following function. Hovering over the route displays the estimated distance and duration.

In[31]:
import folium
from datetime import timedelta

def show_route(route: Dict[str, Any]) -> folium.Map:
    map = folium.Map(tiles=None)
    folium.TileLayer('OpenStreetmap', control=False).add_to(map)
    mm, _ = divmod(timedelta(seconds=route['duration']).seconds, 60)
    hh, mm = divmod(mm, 60)
    folium.GeoJson(
        route['geometry'],
        style_function=lambda x: {'color': 'black'},
        tooltip=f"""
          <b>Distancia total:</b> {route['distance']:.1f} km<br>
          <b>Tiempo estimado:</b> {hh} h, {mm} min<br>
        """,
        control=False,
    ).add_to(map)
    start = Point(route['geometry'].coords[0])
    folium.Marker(
        location=[start.y, start.x],    # folium sigue orden (lat, lon) en lugar de (lon, lat)
        icon=folium.Icon(color='red', icon="car", prefix="fa"),   # smbolo de gasolinera
        tooltip=f"<b>Inicio:</b> ({start.x:.3f}, {start.y:.3f})<br>",
    ).add_to(map)
    end = Point(route['geometry'].coords[-1])
    folium.Marker(
        location=[end.y, end.x],    # folium sigue orden (lat, lon) en lugar de (lon, lat)
        icon=folium.Icon(color='red', icon="flag-checkered", prefix="fa"),
        tooltip=f"<b>Final:</b> ({end.x:.3f}, {end.y:.3f})<br>",
    ).add_to(map)
    bbox = route['bbox']
    map.fit_bounds([(bbox[1], bbox[0]), (bbox[3], bbox[2])])
    return map

3.6 Distances to Gas Stations

Once a route is obtained, it is straightforward to determine which gas stations are on or near it. To do this, we can use the following function, which optionally accepts two parameters:

  • max_detour (default 30 km): the maximum distance a gas station can be from the route.
  • max_stations (default 100): the maximum number of gas stations to consider.
In[33]:
from pyproj import Transformer

SPAIN_CRS = 'epsg:32630'

def select_closest_stations(
    route: Dict[str, Any], stations_prices: gpd.GeoDataFrame, fuel_id: int,
    max_detour: int = 30, max_stations: int = 100,
) -> gpd.GeoDataFrame:

    transformer = Transformer.from_crs('WGS84', SPAIN_CRS, always_xy=True)
    coords = route['geometry'].coords
    route_geometry = LineString([transformer.transform(x, y) for x, y in coords])

    straight_line = LineString([route_geometry.coords[0], route_geometry.coords[-1]])

    stations_prices = stations_prices.xs(fuel_id, level=1).to_crs(SPAIN_CRS)

    stations_prices.loc[:, 'detour'] = stations_prices.distance(route_geometry) / 1000

    closest_stations = stations_prices[stations_prices['detour'] <= max_detour]

    along_route = [0 < straight_line.project(p, normalized=True) < 1 for p in closest_stations['location']]
    closest_stations = closest_stations.loc[along_route, :]

    closest_stations = closest_stations.nsmallest(max_stations, 'detour')

    closest_stations.loc[:, 'from_start'] = [route_geometry.project(p) / 1000 for p in closest_stations['location']]    # en km tambin

    return closest_stations.to_crs('WGS84').sort_values('from_start')

4. Problem Solution - Part A

4.1 Auxiliar Functions

We will create functions that, given certain parameters, allow us to obtain results for different combinations.

The following function allows us to create a sub-dictionary from a given dictionary up to a specific key. In particular, it returns a sub-dictionary containing all elements up to the key immediately preceding the specified one.

We will use this function later.

In[35]:
from typing import Dict

def get_sub_dict(dictionary: Dict[int, str], limit_key: int) -> Dict[int, str]:
    filtered_dict = {}
    for key, value in dictionary.items():
        if key == limit_key:
            break
        filtered_dict[key] = value
    return filtered_dict

4.2 Functions for the Optimization Problem

The following function will be used to define the variables of the problem.

In[36]:
def define_variables(stats: List[str]):
  fuel_liters = LpVariable.dicts("liters", indices=stats, lowBound=0, cat=LpContinuous)
  stop_station = LpVariable.dicts("stop_station", indices=stats, cat=LpBinary)
  return fuel_liters, stop_station

Additionally, we define a function that creates the fuel cost minimization problem in PuLP.

In[37]:
def create_fuel_cost_problem(stats: List[int], fuel_price: pd.Series, fuel_liters:  Dict[int,LpVariable]):
  prob = LpProblem("Fuel_cost", LpMinimize)
  prob += lpSum([fuel_price[i] * fuel_liters[i] for i in stats])
  return prob

We also create a function that adds the constraints to the optimization problem.

In[38]:
from typing import List
def add_constraints(prob: LpProblem, stats: List[int], fuel_price: pd.Series, from_start: pd.Series,
                    detour: pd.Series, route_distance: float, fuel_liters: Dict[int,LpVariable],
                    stop_station: Dict[int,LpVariable], initial_fuel_level: float,
                    min_fuel_level: float, max_fuel_level: float, consumption: float):
  for s in stats:
    sum_liters = lpSum(fuel_liters[j] for j in get_sub_dict(fuel_liters,s).keys())
    sum_detour = lpSum(detour[j]*stop_station[j] for j in get_sub_dict(fuel_liters,s).keys())
    c_s = initial_fuel_level + sum_liters - (consumption/100)*(from_start[s] + 2*sum_detour)

    prob += (c_s >= min_fuel_level + (consumption/100)*detour[s]*stop_station[s])
    prob += (max_fuel_level >= c_s + fuel_liters[s] - (consumption/100)*(detour[s]*stop_station[s]))
    prob += (fuel_price[s]*fuel_liters[s] >= 5*stop_station[s])
    prob += (fuel_liters[s] <= max_fuel_level*stop_station[s])

  total_liters = lpSum(fuel_liters[i] for i in fuel_liters.keys())
  total_detours = lpSum(detour[i]*stop_station[i] for i in stop_station.keys())

  final_fuel_amount = initial_fuel_level + total_liters - (consumption/100)*(route_distance + 2*total_detours)
  prob += (final_fuel_amount >= min_fuel_level)

  return prob

The following function will help us display all the requested results.

In[39]:
def get_solutions_cost(prob: LpProblem, fuel_price: pd.Series, from_start: pd.Series,
                       detour: pd.Series, route_distance: float ,fuel_liters: Dict[str, LpVariable],
                       stop_station: Dict[str, LpVariable], initial_fuel_level: float, consumption: float):
  status = prob.solve()
  solution = prob.objective.value()
  detour_sum = 0
  total_liters = 0
  stops_info = []

  for index, variable in stop_station.items():
    if variable.varValue != 0:
      from_start_stat = from_start[index]
      detour_stat = detour[index]
      distance_to_stat = from_start_stat + detour_stat
      fuel_amount_stat= fuel_liters[index].varValue
      fuel_price_stat = fuel_price[index]
      expense_stat = fuel_price_stat*fuel_amount_stat

      detour_sum += 2*detour_stat
      total_liters += fuel_amount_stat

      stops_info.append({
          'num_stat': index,
          'liters_stat': fuel_amount_stat,
          'distance_to_stat': distance_to_stat,
          'fuel_price_stat': fuel_price_stat
      })

      print(f"Stopping at gas station {index}")
      print(f"Distance from the start of the route to gas station {index}: {distance_to_stat}km")
      print(f"Liters/kilograms refueled at gas station {index}: {fuel_amount_stat}")
      print(f"Fuel price at gas station {index}: {fuel_price_stat} per liter or kilogram\n\n\n")


  total_distance = route_distance + detour_sum
  final_fuel_amount = initial_fuel_level + total_liters - (consumption/100)*(total_distance)

  print(f"The total distance traveled is {total_distance}km")
  print(f"The total cost is {solution}")
  print(f"The final fuel amount is {final_fuel_amount} (liters or kg)\n\n\n")


  return stops_info

Finally, optimize_fuel_cost uses all the previous functions to solve the problem.

In[40]:
def optimize_fuel_cost(gdf: gpd.GeoDataFrame, start_point: Point, end_point: Point,
                       fuel_id: int, tank_capacity:float, consumption: float = 4.5):

    initial_fuel_level = tank_capacity/2
    max_fuel_level = tank_capacity
    min_fuel_level = (consumption/100)*60

    route = get_route(start= start_point, end= end_point, api_key=API_KEY)
    closest = select_closest_stations(route, gdf, fuel_id)
    closest = closest[closest.side != 'I']

    stats = closest.index.tolist()
    fuel_price = closest['price']
    from_start = closest['from_start']
    detour = closest['detour']
    route_distance = route['distance']

    fuel_liters, stop_station = define_variables(stats)

    prob = create_fuel_cost_problem(stats, fuel_price, fuel_liters)
    prob = add_constraints(prob, stats, fuel_price, from_start, detour, route_distance,
                           fuel_liters, stop_station, initial_fuel_level,min_fuel_level, max_fuel_level, consumption)

    return get_solutions_cost(prob, fuel_price, from_start, detour, route_distance,fuel_liters,stop_station, initial_fuel_level, consumption)

4.3 Functions for Creating Maps

We create a function to add pop-ups, based on the elements of a dictionary containing information about each stop.

In[41]:
def create_pop_up(stop: Dict[str,float]):
  popup_info = f"""<div style="width: 200px; white-space: nowrap;">
              <strong> Fuel Station {stop['num_stat']}</strong><br>
              <strong> Fuel:</strong> {stop['liters_stat']:.2f} L<br>
              <strong> Distance:</strong> {stop['distance_to_stat']:.2f} km<br>
              <strong> Price:</strong> {stop['fuel_price_stat']:.2f} /L
              </div>
              """

  if 'time_to_stat' in stop:
    popup_info += f"<strong> Time since the start of the trip:</strong> {stop['time_to_stat']:.2f} h<br>"

  return popup_info

We create another function to generate plots of the route, stops, and associated information, using the previously defined show_route function:

In[42]:
import folium
from folium import plugins
from folium.features import DivIcon

def create_route_stops_map(stops_info: List[Dict[str,float]], gdf: gpd.GeoDataFrame = gdf,
                           start_point: Point = Point(-3.70256, 40.4165), end_point: Point = Point(2.15899, 41.38879)):

    route = get_route(start= start_point, end= end_point, api_key=API_KEY)
    route_map = show_route(route)

    center_map = (40.4165, -3.70256)

    for i, stop in enumerate(stops_info):
        station = gdf.loc[(gdf.index.get_level_values(0) == stop['num_stat'])].iloc[0]

        lat = station['location'].y
        lon = station['location'].x
        popup_info = create_pop_up(stop)
        folium.Marker(
            location=[lat, lon],
            popup=popup_info,
            tooltip=f"Parada {stop['num_stat']}",
            icon=DivIcon(
                icon_size=(30, 30),
                icon_anchor=(15, 15),
                html=f'<div style="font-size: 12pt; color: white; background-color: #007bff; border-radius: 50%; width: 25px; height: 25px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;">{i+1}</div>'
            )
        ).add_to(route_map)


    return route_map

4.4.4 Comparison of gasoline fuels

5 Problem Solution - Part B

5.1 Functions

Similarly to Part A, we will create different functions to solve the problem. Some of the functions defined in the previous part will also be used.

We define a function that creates the corresponding optimization problem:

In[88]:
def create_time_problem(stats: List[int], detour: pd.Series, avg_speed: float,
                        fuel_liters: Dict[int, LpVariable], stop_station: Dict[int, LpVariable]):
  prob = LpProblem("Time", LpMinimize)
  prob += lpSum([(2*detour[i]/avg_speed)*stop_station[i] + fuel_liters[i]*(1 / 1200) +(5/60)*stop_station[i] for i in stats])
  return prob

As before, we create a function to display all the necessary results:

In[89]:
def get_solutions_time(prob: LpProblem, fuel_price: pd.Series, from_start: pd.Series,
                       detour: pd.Series, route_distance: float, avg_speed: float,
                       fuel_liters: Dict[int, LpVariable], stop_station: Dict[int, LpVariable],
                       initial_fuel_level: float, consumption:float):

  status = prob.solve()
  detour_time = prob.objective.value()
  detour_sum = 0
  total_expense = 0
  total_liters = 0
  stops_info = []

  for index, variable in stop_station.items():
    if variable.varValue != 0:
      from_start_stat = from_start[index]
      detour_stat = detour[index]
      distance_to_stat = from_start_stat + detour_stat
      time_to_stat = distance_to_stat/avg_speed
      fuel_amount_stat= fuel_liters[index].varValue
      fuel_price_stat = fuel_price[index]
      expense_stat = fuel_price_stat*fuel_amount_stat

      detour_sum += 2*detour_stat
      total_expense += expense_stat
      total_liters += fuel_amount_stat

      stops_info.append({
          'num_stat': index,
          'liters_stat': fuel_amount_stat,
          'distance_to_stat': distance_to_stat,
          'time_to_stat': time_to_stat,
          'fuel_price_stat': fuel_price_stat
      })

      print(f"Stopping at gas station {index}")
      print(f"Distance from the start of the route to gas station {index}: {distance_to_stat}km")
      print(f"Liters/kilograms refueled at gas station {index}: {fuel_amount_stat}")
      print(f"Time from the start of the trip to reach gas station {index}: {time_to_stat}h\n\n\n")

  total_distance = route_distance + detour_sum
  final_fuel_amount = initial_fuel_level + total_liters - (consumption/100)*(total_distance)
  total_time = detour_time + (total_distance/avg_speed)

  print(f"The total distance traveled is {total_distance}km")
  print(f"The total expense is {total_expense}")
  print(f"The final fuel amount is {final_fuel_amount} (liters or kg)")
  print(f"The total time is {total_time}h")

  return stops_info

Finally, the function that allows us to solve the entire problem by calling it:

In[90]:
def optimize_time(gdf: gpd.GeoDataFrame, start_point: Point, end_point: Point,
                  fuel_id: int, tank_capacity:float, consumption: float = 4.5):

    initial_fuel_level = tank_capacity/2
    max_fuel_level = tank_capacity
    min_fuel_level = (consumption/100)*60

    route = get_route(start= start_point, end= end_point, api_key=API_KEY)
    closest = select_closest_stations(route, gdf, fuel_id)
    closest = closest[closest.side != 'I']
    closest = closest[closest.open_times == 'L-D: 24H']

    stats = closest.index.tolist()
    fuel_price = closest['price']
    from_start = closest['from_start']
    detour = closest['detour']
    route_distance = route['distance']
    avg_speed = route['distance'] / (route['duration'] / 3600)

    fuel_liters, stop_station = define_variables(stats)

    prob = create_time_problem(stats, detour, avg_speed, fuel_liters, stop_station)
    prob = add_constraints(prob, stats, fuel_price, from_start, detour, route_distance, fuel_liters, stop_station, initial_fuel_level,
                           min_fuel_level, max_fuel_level, consumption)

    return get_solutions_time(prob, fuel_price, from_start, detour, route_distance, avg_speed,
                       fuel_liters, stop_station, initial_fuel_level, consumption)
